<font color="#FF0000">VIET NAM MEMORIAL</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 19  1:01:03 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
<br>
As a peace time pre Viet Nam draftee, I lived my life at home through the period of the war with various thoughts and feelings, none of them very deep or frequent.  A visit to the Wall affected me the same way that it appears to have affected thousands.  The only analogy that seems close in my experience is the way I was affected by the death of my father.  The facts are known, the intellect accepts, but confrontation with the fact brings an upwelling of grief and tears of the heart, with the remembrance of his many sacrifices and his love for me. <br><br>
 I can't claim the Viet nam experience, but I can claim the duty and privilege to honor and remember those whose names are written on the Wall.  If the purpose of a Memorial is to make us remember, then I cannot conceive of a more effective one.<br><br>

<p><code>-- lacpsmi@open.org  (Lloyd Smith) </code><p>


